const faqs = [
  { q: "Is it legal to take direct bookings instead of using Airbnb?", a: "Yes, completely legal. Airbnb does not have an exclusivity clause. You can accept bookings through your own website, by phone, or through any other channel. You still need to comply with your local STR regulations (licensing, night limits, MAT tax collection), but how you accept bookings is entirely your choice." },
  { q: "How much can I save by taking direct bookings?", a: "Since December 2025, Airbnb charges hosts a flat 15.5% service fee on every booking. On a $200/night booking for 3 nights ($600), Airbnb takes $93. On a 30-night stay at $100/night, that's $465 gone to Airbnb. Direct bookings eliminate that fee entirely. Even after Stripe's 2.9% processing fee, you keep significantly more per booking." },
  { q: "Do I need a professional website for direct bookings?", a: "Not necessarily. A simple one-page site with property photos, an availability calendar, pricing, and a booking/inquiry form is enough to start. Platforms like Lodgify, Hospitable, and Hostaway offer templates specifically designed for vacation rental hosts. You can have a professional site live in a weekend." },
  { q: "How do I handle payments for direct bookings?", a: "Stripe is the most popular option for vacation rental hosts. It integrates with most booking platforms, charges 2.9% + $0.30 per transaction, and handles security deposits. Square and PayPal are alternatives. Always use a payment processor rather than accepting e-transfers or cash to protect both parties and maintain a clear record." },
  { q: "What about guest screening without Airbnb's verification?", a: "Several third-party services handle guest screening for direct bookings. Autohost, Guest Ranger, and Superhog offer ID verification, background checks, and damage protection. These services cost $5-$15 per reservation and provide verification standards that often exceed what Airbnb offers." },
